Currently in Longyearbyen, Svalbard - about to board MV Villa with @arildheitmannphotography and 11 excited clients 😁

Wish us luck, there's lots of snow and sea ice!
Svalbard 2023, an amazing experience from start to finish. While we mostly focus on landscapes during our tours, we had eight encounters with polar bears! Pictures to follow 🙏

Svalbard VII, April 2022.

The furthest north we could go, 80°06.533 - just entering the 80th parallel circle. The sea ice and wind conditions coming down from the North Pole forced us to turn around, and we could all sense the machinist being anxious as the ship's plumbing started to freeze before our very eyes! According to the captain, it was -36 degrees celsius plus windchill 🥶😁 gotta love the adventure!

Svalbard VIII, April 2022.

This place has a magnetic pull that is impossible to explain in simple words. Understandably, it's not a place for everyone - but for those of us who thrive the cold Arctic, it claims a piece of your heart forever.

Svalbard X, April 2022.

The Grinch looking for his next prey. There were six reindeer carcases within a few kilometers radius, so this bear was very well fed!

Bide-Mahpe I, Yellowstone - January 2023

Indian tribes in Yellowstone National Park were not afraid of the springs. Quite the opposite as there is evidence that they made use of the springs for cooking food, and bathed in the water for medicinal purposes. On occasion they also buried their dead in the bubbling water.

Such springs were regarded as having spiritual significance. Certainly it is true that they believed it was full of spirits. But these spirits were not malevolent, as maintained by the modern myth-makers, but friendly and helpful. Native American names for Yellowstone invariably referred to its thermal properties, such as “many smoke” or “place of hot water”. More explicitly, the Crow nation called the geysers bide-mahpe - meaning “sacred or powerful water".
